We talked   last Thursday about a weird little acquisition of The Children=
=E2=80=99s Place Inc., a children=E2=80=99s apparel retailer with an equity=
 market capitalization of $363 million as of last Friday. The Children=E2=
=80=99s Place got acquired=C2=A0last week in the simplest and yet most unus=
ual possible way: Someone just went to the stock exchange and kept buying s=
tock until they owned a majority of it. Then they sent the company a letter=
 saying =E2=80=9Chi we=E2=80=99re your new owners now.=E2=80=9D It=E2=80=99=
s the way you would buy a public company if you had a lot of money and knew=
 nothing about mergers and acquisitions. Just keep hitting the Buy button o=
n your Robinhood app until you control the company.
The buyer  is=C2=A0=E2=80=9Cthe Al-Rajhi family, the founders of Saudi Arab=
ia=E2=80=99s largest private bank,=E2=80=9D through vehicles including Mith=
aq Capital SPC and the wonderfully=C2=A0named Snowball Compounding Ltd. Las=
t Friday, Mithaq=C2=A0filed a Schedule 13D explaining their trades and plan=
s. Apparently they own=C2=A0just over 7 million shares of The Children=E2=
=80=99s Place, or about 56.1% of the stock, and =E2=80=9Care proud to be ma=
jority owners of the Issuer, are enthusiastic about its long-term prospects=
 and look forward to helping it thrive and deliver top quality products to =
families.=E2=80=9D They were  trading the stock starting at least in early =
January, but they bought and sold; they didn=E2=80=99t start accumulating i=
t in earnest until about Feb. 7, and went from a small stake to a majority =
in five trading days.
Also=C2=A0they weren=E2=80=99t=C2=A0just=C2=A0aimlessly buying stock: On Sa=
turday, Feb. 10, when Mithaq had accumulated  about 3.1 million shares=C2=
=A0(about 25%), Snowball Compounding sent the company a notice that it inte=
nded to replace the board of directors with its own nominees. On Wednesday,=
 Feb. 14, when they had=C2=A0gotten to 54%, Mithaq and Snowball  sent anoth=
er letter to the board, asking =E2=80=9Cto meet with you as soon as possibl=
e so that we can discuss an orderly transition of the governance of the Com=
pany, as well as the provision of financing to assist the Company with its =
liquidity needs.=E2=80=9D=C2=A0So they=C2=A0definitely had a plan to take c=
ontrol of the company. They just figured that the most efficient way to do =
that was to buy in the open market.=C2=A0
And that was clearly correct! The stock was trading above $20 for most of t=
he last few months, but then crashed below $13 on Friday, Feb. 9, after the=
 company announced  terrible earnings. Mithaq paid about $97.8 million for =
its 7 million shares, an average=C2=A0of about $13.97 per share. That=E2=80=
=99s lower than the lowest the stock had traded over the previous year. Mea=
nwhile,=C2=A0after=C2=A0Mithaq=E2=80=99s interest got out, the stock shot u=
p; it closed last Friday at $29.12. The bad earnings left investors worried=
 that The Children=E2=80=99s Place might run out of money; the arrival of a=
 deep-pocketed buyer solved that problem and squeezed the stock up.=C2=A0Mi=
thaq saved a lot of money by buying quickly but=C2=A0quietly.=C2=A0Some mor=
e formal process =E2=80=94=C2=A0sending the board a merger proposal, launch=
ing a tender offer =E2=80=94=C2=A0would have betrayed its interest and push=
ed up the price.
If you were The Children=E2=80=99s Place, and you got that nomination notic=
e on Feb. 10, might you have wanted to make it public? Put out a press rele=
ase like =E2=80=9Chey, we got a letter from somebody named Snowball saying =
that they own 25% of our stock and want to replace our board=E2=80=9D? I ge=
t that that=E2=80=99s a somewhat weird thing to announce; for all I know th=
e company had never heard of Mithaq before and didn=E2=80=99t know how seri=
ously to take the nomination.
  [3]
 But if the company had publicized the letter, I suppose the shareholders w=
ould have had some warning that=C2=A0there was some interest, and journalis=
ts could have, like, called Mithaq and said =E2=80=9Cwhat=E2=80=99s up?=E2=
=80=9D As it is, the stock closed at a low of $11.29 last Tuesday, just bef=
ore Mithaq started  disclosing its ownership. Mithaq bought almost a millio=
n shares that day.
Mithaq had no obligation to disclose what it was doing =E2=80=94=C2=A0or, r=
ather, it did=C2=A0have=C2=A0obligations to disclose, but with some delay, =
and it followed those obligations scrupulously.
  [4]
 It disclosed its purchases as soon as it was obligated to, but by the time=
 it disclosed them it had more or less completed its buying.
  [5]
=C2=A0It might have been nice, for The Children=E2=80=99s Place=E2=80=99s e=
xisting shareholders, if the company had told them about the mysterious buy=
er. But it didn=E2=80=99t, so Mithaq was able to buy most of the stock with=
out anyone noticing.
What happens to the rest of the shareholders? Mithaq bought control of the =
company for less than $14 per share; presumably it doesn=E2=80=99t want to =
buy the remaining 44% for $29 per share. If you=E2=80=99re a minority share=
holder, you=E2=80=99re kind of along for a weird ride now.=C2=A0
By the way, I said last week, and again above, that this is a pretty unusua=
l way to acquire a public company. =E2=80=9CI=E2=80=99m sure someone has do=
ne this before,=E2=80=9D I wrote,=C2=A0=E2=80=9Cbut it is very much not nor=
mal practice.=E2=80=9D That is perhaps too modern a view, and some readers =
pointed out that some flavor of =E2=80=9Cbuy in the open market until you h=
it 51%=E2=80=9D=C2=A0used=C2=A0to be a bit more normal in US M&A practice.
For instance,=C2=A0in hostile M&A deals in the 1980s, the =E2=80=9Cstreet s=
weep=E2=80=9D was a fairly common  takeover practice. This was a form of op=
en-market buying to get a majority of the stock, though it=E2=80=99s a bit =
different from the approach with The Children=E2=80=99s Place=C2=A0in that =
it was typically done=C2=A0after=C2=A0a public takeover contest was announc=
ed. The idea is that you launch a tender offer or other hostile bid, and th=
at attracts attention from merger arbitrageurs. The stock turns over: The n=
ormal long-term investors sell, and the arbitrageurs buy. Then a potential =
buyer goes out to the arbitrageurs and buys their stock from them directly,=
 getting a big chunk of shares =E2=80=94=C2=A0perhaps a majority=C2=A0=E2=
=80=94=C2=A0without messing around with a tender offer.=C2=A0
But even the approach with The Children=E2=80=99s Place =E2=80=94 buying in=
 the open market without=C2=A0any public contest or negotiated purchases =
=E2=80=94=C2=A0has happened before. In particular, that is how Warren Buffe=
tt acquired control of Berkshire Hathaway Inc. in the 1960s: As he once put=
 it, he was a smallish shareholder, but then the company =E2=80=9Cmade me v=
ery mad, so I just started buying more stock=E2=80=9D; eventually =E2=80=9C=
I bought enough so we controlled the company, and we changed the management=
.=E2=80=9D It=E2=80=99s entirely possible that that=E2=80=99s what just hap=
pened at The Children=E2=80=99s Place, too.

