      Pre-capitalizations
   =20
 =20

Meanwhile in more normal M&A, a common form of acquisition is the leveraged=
 buyout (LBO) by a private equity firm: Some company puts itself up for auc=
tion, a few private equity firms bid, and one of them wins and buys the com=
pany. The buyer generally borrows a lot of the money needed to buy the comp=
any, with that borrowing coming either from bonds and loans underwritten by=
 one or more big banks, or (more recently) from private credit lenders. Tra=
ditionally that lending business is a huge (though risky) source of revenue=
 for the banks, who can make more on the fees from the financing than they =
do on mergers-and-acquisitions advisory fees.
And so a certain amount of M&A structuring is built around banks=E2=80=99 d=
esire to get financing fees. For instance, traditionally, the company selli=
ng itself will hire a bank as an=C2=A0adviser, and the potential buyers wil=
l each hire their own bank, who will advise them on the deal and also provi=
de their=C2=A0financing (if they win the auction). But this means that the =
company=E2=80=99s bankers won=E2=80=99t get any financing fees, which is a =
bummer for them. So some deals come with =E2=80=9Cstapled financing,=E2=80=
=9D in which the seller=E2=80=99s bankers offer to provide financing for=C2=
=A0the winning bidder: This perhaps  makes the auction more competitive, bu=
t it also means that the seller=E2=80=99s bankers have a chance to get fina=
ncing fees.
I guess another option would be to do the financing first=C2=A0and=C2=A0the=
n=C2=A0sell the company? Like, if you are a company that might want to sell=
 itself (or the company=E2=80=99s banker), you can probably build an LBO mo=
del yourself and estimate roughly what sort of capital structure =E2=80=94=
=C2=A0how much borrowing, what kind and at what rates =E2=80=94=C2=A0a priv=
ate equity borrower might want. And then you go do the borrowing yourself. =
And then you run the auction, and say to potential buyers =E2=80=9Chey this=
 capital structure is already set up so nice for you, all we need is your e=
quity check.=E2=80=9D=C2=A0
Why not. Bloomberg=E2=80=99s=C2=A0Eleanor Duncan and Michael Tobin report=
=C2=A0that big banks are trying to win business back from private credit, b=
oth by sort of lowering their standards and by offering =E2=80=9Cpre-capita=
liations=E2=80=9D:

Traditional lenders are so keen to win leveraged buyout financing that some=
 are pitching for subordinated debt deals =E2=80=94 the riskiest type of un=
derwriting which they mostly avoided during a bruising past few years. At l=
east one bank is offering payment-in-kind options, which allow interest pay=
ments to be deferred, and others are talking to borrowers about so-called p=
re-capitalizations, which give companies financing before a deal has even g=
one on the block, according to people familiar with the matter. =E2=80=A6
The quest to win fees is driving some banks, including Bank of America, to =
pitch pre-capitalizations to companies that aren=E2=80=99t even for sale ye=
t, according to a person familiar with the matter. In these deals, lenders =
refinance a firm=E2=80=99s debt and add a portability clause, allowing a ne=
w buyer to keep the existing debt package in place. Bankers say it makes it=
 easier for companies to be sold at a later date because the new owner does=
n=E2=80=99t have to find financing.

Presumably this makes the most sense for companies with private equity owne=
rs (who might shop them to=C2=A0new private equity owners), which already h=
ave LBO-ish capital structures that they just want to be portable.

