      Shadow trading
   =20
 =20

If you worked at Pfizer Inc. in 2021, and you got early notice of Pfizer=E2=
=80=99s successful clinical trial of Paxlovid, its Covid-19 treatment, you =
could have bought call options on Pfizer=E2=80=99s stock and made a lot of =
money when the results were announced and the stock went up. And then you w=
ould have gotten very arrested, because that=E2=80=99s illegal insider trad=
ing. And in fact a Pfizer employee allegedly did do=C2=A0that, and   got ar=
rested.
Or=C2=A0you could have bought call options on Royal Caribbean Cruise Ltd.=
=E2=80=99s stock and made a lot of money when the Paxlovid results were ann=
ounced. Because Royal Caribbean=E2=80=99s stock=C2=A0did=C2=A0go up 8% that=
 day. It was maybe not=C2=A0the most obvious thing in the world=C2=A0that R=
oyal Caribbean would go up because Paxlovid worked, but nor was it all that=
=C2=A0surprising; if you were paying attention to the world, you could have=
 had some thought process like =E2=80=9Cfew businesses were hit harder by C=
ovid than cruises, and a cure for Covid is going to make it easier for peop=
le to go back on cruise ships, so Royal Caribbean should go up a lot.=E2=80=
=9D And you would have been right and made a lot of money.
This is sometimes called =E2=80=9Cshadow trading,=E2=80=9D using your insid=
e information about one company (say, your employer) to make informed trade=
s on some other company that will also be affected by the news.
But would you have gotten arrested? Well! Well. We have   talked a few   ti=
mes about the US Securities and Exchange Commission=E2=80=99s insider tradi=
ng case against Matthew Panuwat, who is accused of shadow trading on merger=
 news. (He allegedly knew his employer was getting acquired, so he bought o=
ptions on a competitor, whose stock also went up on the acquisition news.) =
Today the Wall Street Journal  covers the case:

The case, which goes to trial next month, has become the latest test of ins=
ider-trading law. Congress has never defined what it means, leaving regulat=
ors and courts across the country to decide what qualifies, a volatile proc=
ess that sometimes leads appellate courts to rein in what they see as exces=
ses.=C2=A0
Defense lawyers have dubbed Panuwat=E2=80=99s case the first involving =E2=
=80=9Cshadow insider trading,=E2=80=9D a label that describes executives ma=
king well-timed bets in the shares of other companies. =E2=80=A6
No court has ever tackled the idea that executives can go too far when they=
 deploy their specialized knowledge or expertise to trade in the shares of =
rivals, said Karen Woody, a professor at the Washington and Lee University =
School of Law.=C2=A0
=E2=80=9CI do think this is a push of the law and they are seeing if they c=
an get a court to bless what is a bit of a stretch of the existing paramete=
rs,=E2=80=9D Woody said of the SEC=E2=80=99s case.

I mean, on the one hand, that=E2=80=99s true, but on the other hand, imagin=
e if the court said =E2=80=9Cnah that just isn=E2=80=99t insider trading=E2=
=80=9D? (I don=E2=80=99t think that=E2=80=99s likely, since the judge has d=
eclined to dismiss the case. The SEC might still lose at trial, but if it d=
oes, that will probably be an inscrutable jury verdict that doesn't really =
define the law for future cases. But if the SEC wins at trial, Panuwat coul=
d appeal, and then an appeals court could still say =E2=80=9Cnah, not insid=
er trading.=E2=80=9D) Then every=C2=A0sophisticated=C2=A0corporate insider =
=E2=80=94=C2=A0also, sorry, every Money Stuff reader =E2=80=94=C2=A0would h=
ave a blueprint for how to do insider trading legally. You find out your co=
mpany=E2=80=99s news and you go trade the most correlated stock.=C2=A0
I have said this before, but for years readers have emailed me with some va=
riation on this idea. =E2=80=9CIf I have inside information about my compan=
y, can I trade our competitor=E2=80=99s stock, knowing that the news is pro=
bably good for them too?=E2=80=9D My general thoughts on this question used=
 to be (1) nothing here is ever legal advice, (2) the SEC=C2=A0wouldn=E2=80=
=99t like it and (3) the law is arguably a little unclear, since there are =
no real precedents. That state of affairs probably deterred at least some p=
eople from doing shadow trading: Why do something the SEC thinks is illegal=
, even if the law is unclear?
But now the SEC has brought a case, which has the advantage and disadvantag=
e that it might resolve the ambiguity. On the one hand, now you=C2=A0defini=
tely=C2=A0know that the SEC doesn=E2=80=99t like shadow trading, which migh=
t be an additional deterrent. On the other hand, what if the SEC loses? Wha=
t if the answer is =E2=80=9Cnot legal advice, the SEC won=E2=80=99t like it=
, but courts say=C2=A0it=E2=80=99s allowed so there=E2=80=99s nothing the S=
EC can do about it=E2=80=9D? I suspect that will mean much more shadow trad=
ing.=C2=A0

