<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">A <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusine=
ss.com/click/34412285.257387/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21iZXJnLmNvbS9vcGluaW9uL2=
FydGljbGVzLzIwMjQtMDItMDgvYmlsbC1hY2ttYW4td2FudHMteW91ci1tb25leT9jbXBpZD1CQ=
kQwMjIwMjRfTU9ORVlTVFVGRiZ1dG1fbWVkaXVtPWVtYWlsJnV0bV9zb3VyY2U9bmV3c2xldHRl=
ciZ1dG1fdGVybT0yNDAyMjAmdXRtX2NhbXBhaWduPW1vbmV5c3R1ZmY/607f07ceef4b8524a31=
9a23cB8f92ac52" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_b=
lank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bot=
tom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; b=
ackground-color: #ccc;">  couple</a> of <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloomb=
ergbusiness.com/click/34412285.257387/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21iZXJnLmNvbS9vc=
GluaW9uL2FydGljbGVzLzIwMjQtMDItMTIvd2hhdC1pZi10ZXNsYS1jYW4tdC1sZWF2ZT9jbXBp=
ZD1CQkQwMjIwMjRfTU9ORVlTVFVGRiZ1dG1fbWVkaXVtPWVtYWlsJnV0bV9zb3VyY2U9bmV3c2x=
ldHRlciZ1dG1fdGVybT0yNDAyMjAmdXRtX2NhbXBhaWduPW1vbmV5c3R1ZmY/607f07ceef4b85=
24a319a23cBa1c25093" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=
=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; bord=
er-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: so=
lid; background-color: #ccc;">  times</a> recently, I have contrasted Bill =
Ackman=E2=80=99s old-school approach to managing a hedge fund =E2=80=94=C2=
=A0he=E2=80=99s a famous guy, he makes concentrated=C2=A0high-conviction be=
ts on stocks, he doesn=E2=80=99t hedge much =E2=80=94=C2=A0with the more sc=
ientific modern approach of multimanager multistrategy =E2=80=9Cpod shop=E2=
=80=9D funds, which hire many portfolio managers to make distinct bets, hed=
ging out factor exposure and isolating only their alpha, their skill, their=
 excess returns that are not correlated to the broader market. I noted that=
 the old-school approach seems to have become less popular with institution=
al investors, and that the pod shops have an advantage in=C2=A0raising mone=
y and <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/34412285.257=
387/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21iZXJnLmNvbS9vcGluaW9uL2FydGljbGVzLzIwMjQtMDItMTQ=
vbHlmdC1oYWQtYS10eXBvP2NtcGlkPUJCRDAyMjAyNF9NT05FWVNUVUZGJnV0bV9tZWRpdW09ZW=
1haWwmdXRtX3NvdXJjZT1uZXdzbGV0dGVyJnV0bV90ZXJtPTI0MDIyMCZ1dG1fY2FtcGFpZ249b=
W9uZXlzdHVmZg/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB58a828ce" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" ite=
mscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decora=
tion: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #0000=
00; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;">  charging fees</a=
> these days. Ackman=E2=80=99s simple legible approach, meanwhile, appeals =
to retail investors, and he=E2=80=99s out raising money from ordinary inves=
tors=C2=A0and offering lower fees.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">But I neglected to mention one incredibly impo=
rtant advantage of Ackman=E2=80=99s approach, which is that if you do it ri=
ght, you don=E2=80=99t have to=C2=A0<em>do=C2=A0</em>much. Pick like 10 sto=
cks that are going to go up, buy them all, and then chill. Oh, if the stock=
s go=C2=A0<em>down</em>, that creates a lot of work for you: You might have=
 to sell them and buy other stocks (that will go up), you might have to ree=
valuate your process and rethink your life choices, maybe you have to fire =
an analyst and hire a new one, plus you are going to be spending a lot of t=
ime calling up your investors and reassuring them so they don=E2=80=99t wit=
hdraw their money.<a class=3D"footnote-index" href=3D"#footnote-2" style=3D=
"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px=
; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: none !important; backg=
round-color: transparent !important; display: inline-block;">
<span>[2]</span>
</a> But you are trying to pick stocks that go <em>up</em>, ideally ones th=
at go up more than the rest of the market, and if you succeed then you=E2=
=80=99re done for the year. Pick stocks, buy them, watch them go up, go to =
the beach. Or go on Twitter! (Or, now, X.) Spend your days getting in fight=
s online, because your lavishly gainful employment only requires like 45 mi=
nutes of work per year.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Oh, no,=C2=A0I=E2=80=99m exaggerating; obvious=
ly the people who pick 10 good stocks usually spend most of their waking ho=
urs analyzing their stocks, worrying about them, thinking about which ones =
they should drop and which other stocks they should substitute, etc. You do=
n=E2=80=99t become a professional picker of 10 stocks without putting a lot=
 of work into that list of 10 stocks. Still, I have always admired and envi=
ed that old-school model of hedge fund management. It just strikes me as th=
e purest possible way to turn intellect =E2=80=94=C2=A0or something, anyway=
, luck maybe =E2=80=94=C2=A0into money. If some region of your brain is wir=
ed to know what stocks will go up, that=E2=80=99s=C2=A0<em>almost=C2=A0</em=
>all you need; hard work and people skills and a rigorous investing process=
 are just nice bonuses.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Anyway Bloomberg=E2=80=99s <a href=3D"https://=
link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/34412285.257387/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb=
21iZXJnLmNvbS9uZXdzL2FydGljbGVzLzIwMjQtMDItMjAvcmljaGVzdC1oZWRnZS1mdW5kLW1h=
bmFnZXJzLWxlZC1ieS1penp5LWVuZ2xhbmRlci1rZW4tZ3JpZmZpbj9jbXBpZD1CQkQwMjIwMjR=
fTU9ORVlTVFVGRiZ1dG1fbWVkaXVtPWVtYWlsJnV0bV9zb3VyY2U9bmV3c2xldHRlciZ1dG1fdG=
VybT0yNDAyMjAmdXRtX2NhbXBhaWduPW1vbmV5c3R1ZmY/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cBf9e5=
9e5e" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" styl=
e=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width:=
 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-=
color: #ccc;">  Tom Maloney and Hema Parmar report</a>:</p>
<blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Perhaps no other hedge fund manager has perfec=
ted the art of having their money work for them while they sleep =E2=80=94 =
or tweet =E2=80=94 like Bill Ackman.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The Pershing Square Capital Management founder=
 made $610 million last year, after barely touching his portfolio of just 1=
0 stocks. The total landed Ackman at No. 7 on Bloomberg=E2=80=99s annual li=
st of the best-paid hedge fund founders, his highest-ever position. He fail=
ed to crack the top 15 in 2022.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The haul validates Ackman=E2=80=99s shift two =
years ago from a swashbuckling shareholder activist to taking =E2=80=9Ca qu=
ieter approach=E2=80=9D and bringing in a chief investment officer to help =
run his fund. In a year when US stocks soared, his eight-person investment =
team=E2=80=99s stolid approach of holding shares in big companies racked up=
 a 26.7% gain. =E2=80=A6</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">That exceeds the returns for hedge funds inclu=
ding Citadel=E2=80=99s main Wellington strategy (15.3%) and Millennium Mana=
gement (almost 10%), though their founders earned well in excess of Ackman.=
 Millennium=E2=80=99s Izzy Englander nabbed the top spot in Bloomberg=E2=80=
=99s pay ranking with $2.8 billion, while Citadel=E2=80=99s Ken Griffin pla=
ced second at $2.6 billion.</p>
</blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">I mean, sure, right, the S&amp;P 500 index was=
 up 24.2%=C2=A0last year, and Pershing Square <a href=3D"https://link.mail.=
bloombergbusiness.com/click/34412285.257387/aHR0cHM6Ly9hc3NldHMucGVyc2hpbmd=
zcXVhcmVob2xkaW5ncy5jb20vMjAyNC8wMi8wNzExMTQwNS8yMDI0LUFubnVhbC1JbnZlc3Rvci=
1QcmVzZW50YXRpb24ucGRm/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB54943619" itemprop=3D"Story=
Link" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; te=
xt-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-col=
or: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;"> owns</a>=
 basically a long-only portfolio of large-cap US stocks. It had better have=
 been=C2=A0up 26.7%! Its investors got S&amp;P 500 exposure with a little b=
it better performance.=C2=A0Meanwhile, Citadel and Millennium investors wer=
e paying more for somewhat lower returns that are less correlated to the st=
ock market: That particular thing, uncorrelated returns,=C2=A0is an attract=
ive product for many investors, and Citadel and Millennium work very hard t=
o give them that. You have to pay for all that effort. You can pay a bit le=
ss for Ackman=E2=80=99s Zen repose.=C2=A0</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Incidentally, these =E2=80=9Cbest-paid=E2=80=
=9D lists=C2=A0are <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click=
/34412285.257387/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21iZXJnLmNvbS9vcGluaW9uL2FydGljbGVzLz=
IwMTktMDItMTUvZ29vZC1oZWRnZS1mdW5kcy1oYWQtYS1nb29kLXllYXI_Y21waWQ9QkJEMDIyM=
DI0X01PTkVZU1RVRkYmdXRtX21lZGl1bT1lbWFpbCZ1dG1fc291cmNlPW5ld3NsZXR0ZXImdXRt=
X3Rlcm09MjQwMjIwJnV0bV9jYW1wYWlnbj1tb25leXN0dWZm/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB0=
29f6f9c" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" s=
tyle=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-wid=
th: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; backgrou=
nd-color: #ccc;">  always a little debatable</a>; they measure how much mon=
ey these managers made, but that includes returns on their own money in the=
ir funds as well as fee income. Ackman made a lot of money last year becaus=
e he bought stocks that went up. Decent way to do it!</p>
