<h2 style=3D"font-weight: bold; font-family: &quot;Arial Black&quot;, Arial=
, Helvetica, sans-serif; letter-spacing: -1px; font-size: 20px; border-bott=
om-width: 1px; border-bottom-style: dotted; margin: 0px; padding: 16px 0px =
5px;">Children=E2=80=99s Place</h2>
</td>
</tr>
</table>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">We talked <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombe=
rgbusiness.com/click/34412285.257387/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21iZXJnLmNvbS9vcG=
luaW9uL2FydGljbGVzLzIwMjQtMDItMTUvc29tZW9uZS1ib3VnaHQtdGhlLWNoaWxkcmVuLXMtc=
GxhY2U_Y21waWQ9QkJEMDIyMDI0X01PTkVZU1RVRkYmdXRtX21lZGl1bT1lbWFpbCZ1dG1fc291=
cmNlPW5ld3NsZXR0ZXImdXRtX3Rlcm09MjQwMjIwJnV0bV9jYW1wYWlnbj1tb25leXN0dWZm/60=
7f07ceef4b8524a319a23cBa6135d73" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemsc=
ope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !impo=
rtant; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-botto=
m-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;">  last Thursday</a> about a weird =
little acquisition of The Children=E2=80=99s Place Inc., a children=E2=80=
=99s apparel retailer with an equity market capitalization of $363 million =
as of last Friday. The Children=E2=80=99s Place got acquired=C2=A0last week=
 in the simplest and yet most unusual possible way: Someone just went to th=
e stock exchange and kept buying stock until they owned a majority of it. T=
hen they sent the company a letter saying =E2=80=9Chi we=E2=80=99re your ne=
w owners now.=E2=80=9D It=E2=80=99s the way you would buy a public company =
if you had a lot of money and knew nothing about mergers and acquisitions. =
Just keep hitting the Buy button on your Robinhood app until you control th=
e company.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The buyer <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombe=
rgbusiness.com/click/34412285.257387/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuc2VtYWZvci5jb20vbmV3c2=
xldHRlci8wMi8xNS8yMDI0L2Etd2VhbHRoeS1zYXVkaS1mYW1pbHktaXMtYnV5aW5nLXVwLWZha=
WxpbmctY2hpbGRyZW5zLXBsYWNl/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cBa188913a" itemprop=3D"=
StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #00000=
0; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-botto=
m-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;"> is<=
/a>=C2=A0=E2=80=9Cthe Al-Rajhi family, the founders of Saudi Arabia=E2=80=
=99s largest private bank,=E2=80=9D through vehicles including Mithaq Capit=
al SPC and the wonderfully=C2=A0named Snowball Compounding Ltd. Last Friday=
, Mithaq=C2=A0<a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/3441=
2285.257387/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuc2VjLmdvdi9BcmNoaXZlcy9lZGdhci9kYXRhLzEwNDE4NTk=
vMDAwMTEwNDY1OTI0MDI1MDAyL3RtMjQ2NTY1ZDFfc2MxM2QuaHRt/607f07ceef4b8524a319a=
23cB5ddfe324" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_bla=
nk" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-botto=
m-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; bac=
kground-color: #ccc;">filed a Schedule 13D</a> explaining their trades and =
plans. Apparently they own=C2=A0just over 7 million shares of The Children=
=E2=80=99s Place, or about 56.1% of the stock, and =E2=80=9Care proud to be=
 majority owners of the Issuer, are enthusiastic about its long-term prospe=
cts and look forward to helping it thrive and deliver top quality products =
to families.=E2=80=9D They were <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusin=
ess.com/click/34412285.257387/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuc2VjLmdvdi9BcmNoaXZlcy9lZGdhc=
i9kYXRhLzEwNDE4NTkvMDAwMTEwNDY1OTI0MDI1MDAyL3RtMjQ2NTY1ZDFfZXg5OS0yLmh0bQ/6=
07f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB3b386f32" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"items=
cope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !imp=
ortant; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bott=
om-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;"> trading the stock</a> starting a=
t least in early January, but they bought and sold; they didn=E2=80=99t sta=
rt accumulating it in earnest until about Feb. 7, and went from a small sta=
ke to a majority in five trading days.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Also=C2=A0they weren=E2=80=99t=C2=A0<em>just=
=C2=A0</em>aimlessly buying stock: On Saturday, Feb. 10, when Mithaq had ac=
cumulated <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/34412285=
.257387/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuc2VjLmdvdi9BcmNoaXZlcy9lZGdhci9kYXRhLzEwNDE4NTkvMDA=
wMTEwNDY1OTI0MDIyNTUyL3hzbEYzNDVYMDUvdG0yNDYxODItMl80c2VxMS54bWw/607f07ceef=
4b8524a319a23cB6dcd96c7" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" tar=
get=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; b=
order-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style:=
 solid; background-color: #ccc;"> about 3.1 million shares</a>=C2=A0(about =
25%), Snowball Compounding sent the company a notice that it intended to re=
place the board of directors with its own nominees. On Wednesday, Feb. 14, =
when they had=C2=A0gotten to 54%, Mithaq and Snowball <a href=3D"https://li=
nk.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/34412285.257387/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuc2VjLmd=
vdi9BcmNoaXZlcy9lZGdhci9kYXRhLzEwNDE4NTkvMDAwMTEwNDY1OTI0MDI1MDAyL3RtMjQ2NT=
Y1ZDFfZXg5OS0zLmh0bQ/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cBc356f37e" itemprop=3D"StoryLi=
nk" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text=
-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color=
: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;"> sent anoth=
er letter</a> to the board, asking =E2=80=9Cto meet with you as soon as pos=
sible so that we can discuss an orderly transition of the governance of the=
 Company, as well as the provision of financing to assist the Company with =
its liquidity needs.=E2=80=9D=C2=A0So they=C2=A0definitely had a plan to ta=
ke control of the company. They just figured that the most efficient way to=
 do that was to buy in the open market.=C2=A0</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">And that was clearly correct! The stock was tr=
ading above $20 for most of the last few months, but then crashed below $13=
 on Friday, Feb. 9, after the company announced <a href=3D"https://link.mai=
l.bloombergbusiness.com/click/34412285.257387/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cueWV0YW5vdGhlc=
nZhbHVlYmxvZy5jb20vcC90aGUtY3VyaW91cy1jYXNlLW9mLXBsY2UtYW5kLXRoZQ/607f07cee=
f4b8524a319a23cB2aaf18e1" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" ta=
rget=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; =
border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style=
: solid; background-color: #ccc;"> terrible earnings</a>. Mithaq paid about=
 $97.8 million for its 7 million shares, an average=C2=A0of about $13.97 pe=
r share. That=E2=80=99s lower than the lowest the stock had traded over the=
 previous year. Meanwhile,=C2=A0<em>after=C2=A0</em>Mithaq=E2=80=99s intere=
st got out, the stock shot up; it closed last Friday at $29.12. The bad ear=
nings left investors worried that The Children=E2=80=99s Place might run ou=
t of money; the arrival of a deep-pocketed buyer solved that problem and sq=
ueezed the stock up.=C2=A0Mithaq saved a lot of money by buying quickly but=
=C2=A0<em>quietly.=C2=A0</em>Some more formal process =E2=80=94=C2=A0sendin=
g the board a merger proposal, launching a tender offer =E2=80=94=C2=A0woul=
d have betrayed its interest and pushed up the price.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">If you were The Children=E2=80=99s Place, and =
you got that nomination notice on Feb. 10, might you have wanted to make it=
 public? Put out a press release like =E2=80=9Chey, we got a letter from so=
mebody named Snowball saying that they own 25% of our stock and want to rep=
lace our board=E2=80=9D? I get that that=E2=80=99s a somewhat weird thing t=
o announce; for all I know the company had never heard of Mithaq before and=
 didn=E2=80=99t know how seriously to take the nomination.<a class=3D"footn=
ote-index" href=3D"#footnote-3" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: n=
one !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; bor=
der-bottom-style: none !important; background-color: transparent !important=
; display: inline-block;">
<span>[3]</span>
</a> But if the company had publicized the letter, I suppose the shareholde=
rs would have had some warning that=C2=A0there was some interest, and journ=
alists could have, like, called Mithaq and said =E2=80=9Cwhat=E2=80=99s up?=
=E2=80=9D As it is, the stock closed at a low of $11.29 last Tuesday, just =
before Mithaq started <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/cl=
ick/34412285.257387/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuc2VjLmdvdi9BcmNoaXZlcy9lZGdhci9kYXRhLzE=
wNDE4NTkvMDAwMTEwNDY1OTI0MDIyNTUxL3hzbEYzNDVYMDIvdG0yNDYxODItMV8zc2VxMS54bW=
w/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB1d8bdfa2" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"it=
emscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !=
important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-b=
ottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;"> disclosing its ownership</a>.=
 Mithaq bought almost a million shares that day.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Mithaq had no obligation to disclose what it w=
as doing =E2=80=94=C2=A0or, rather, it <em>did=C2=A0</em>have=C2=A0obligati=
ons to disclose, but with some delay, and it followed those obligations scr=
upulously.<a class=3D"footnote-index" href=3D"#footnote-4" style=3D"color: =
#000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border=
-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: none !important; background-co=
lor: transparent !important; display: inline-block;">
<span>[4]</span>
</a> It disclosed its purchases as soon as it was obligated to, but by the =
time it disclosed them it had more or less completed its buying.<a class=3D=
"footnote-index" href=3D"#footnote-5" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decorat=
ion: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #00000=
0; border-bottom-style: none !important; background-color: transparent !imp=
ortant; display: inline-block;">
<span>[5]</span>
</a>=C2=A0It might have been nice, for The Children=E2=80=99s Place=E2=80=
=99s existing shareholders, if <em>the company</em> had told them about the=
 mysterious buyer. But it didn=E2=80=99t, so Mithaq was able to buy most of=
 the stock without anyone noticing.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">What happens to the rest of the shareholders? =
Mithaq bought control of the company for less than $14 per share; presumabl=
y it doesn=E2=80=99t want to buy the remaining 44% for $29 per share. If yo=
u=E2=80=99re a minority shareholder, you=E2=80=99re kind of along for a wei=
rd ride now.=C2=A0</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">By the way, I said last week, and again above,=
 that this is a pretty unusual way to acquire a public company. =E2=80=9CI=
=E2=80=99m sure someone has done this before,=E2=80=9D I wrote,=C2=A0=E2=80=
=9Cbut it is very much not normal practice.=E2=80=9D That is perhaps too mo=
dern a view, and some readers pointed out that some flavor of =E2=80=9Cbuy =
in the open market until you hit 51%=E2=80=9D=C2=A0<em>used=C2=A0</em>to be=
 a bit more normal in US M&amp;A practice.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">For instance,=C2=A0in hostile M&amp;A deals in=
 the 1980s, the =E2=80=9C<a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com=
/click/34412285.257387/aHR0cHM6Ly9zY2hvbGFyc2hpcC5sYXcuZHVrZS5lZHUvY2dpL3Zp=
ZXdjb250ZW50LmNnaT9hcnRpY2xlPTMwNjUmY29udGV4dD1kbGo/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23=
cBcf209dae" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank=
" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-=
width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; backg=
round-color: #ccc;">street sweep</a>=E2=80=9D was a fairly common <a href=
=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/34412285.257387/aHR0cHM6L=
y9jYXNldGV4dC5jb20vY2FzZS9ibGFjay1kZWNrZXItY29ycC12LWFtZXJpY2FuLXN0YW5kYXJk=
LWluYw/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cBd5ede63d" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=
=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: =
none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; bo=
rder-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;"> takeover practice</a>. =
This was a form of open-market buying to get a majority of the stock, thoug=
h it=E2=80=99s a bit different from the approach with The Children=E2=80=99=
s Place=C2=A0in that it was typically done=C2=A0<em>after=C2=A0</em>a publi=
c takeover contest was announced. The idea is that you launch a tender offe=
r or other hostile bid, and that attracts attention from merger arbitrageur=
s. The stock turns over: The normal long-term investors sell, and the arbit=
rageurs buy. Then a potential buyer goes out to the arbitrageurs and buys t=
heir stock from them directly, getting a big chunk of shares =E2=80=94=C2=
=A0perhaps a majority=C2=A0=E2=80=94=C2=A0without messing around with a ten=
der offer.=C2=A0</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">But even the approach with The Children=E2=80=
=99s Place =E2=80=94 buying in the open market <em>without=C2=A0</em>any pu=
blic contest or negotiated purchases =E2=80=94=C2=A0has happened before. In=
 particular, that is how Warren Buffett acquired control of Berkshire Hatha=
way Inc. in the 1960s: As <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.co=
m/click/34412285.257387/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuY25iYy5jb20vMjAxNy8xMi8xMi9idWZmZXR=
0LWJvdWdodC1iZXJrc2hpcmUtaGF0aGF3YXktc2hhcmVzLWZvci03LWRvbGxhcnMtYW5kLTUwLW=
NlbnRzLWVhY2guaHRtbA/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB97c85490" itemprop=3D"StoryLi=
nk" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text=
-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color=
: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;">he once put=
 it</a>, he was a smallish shareholder, but then the company =E2=80=9Cmade =
me very mad, so I just started buying more stock=E2=80=9D; eventually =E2=
=80=9CI bought enough so we controlled the company, and we changed the mana=
gement.=E2=80=9D It=E2=80=99s entirely possible that that=E2=80=99s what ju=
st happened at The Children=E2=80=99s Place, too.</p>
<table class=3D"header" width=3D"100%" border=3D"0" cellspacing=3D"0" cellp=
adding=3D"0">
<tr>
<td class=3D"body-header-container" style=3D"border-collapse: collapse; mso=
-table-lspace: 0pt; mso-table-rspace: 0pt;">
<h2 style=3D"font-weight: bold; font-family: &quot;Arial Black&quot;, Arial=
, Helvetica, sans-serif; letter-spacing: -1px; font-size: 20px; border-bott=
om-width: 1px; border-bottom-style: dotted; margin: 0px; padding: 16px 0px =
5px;">Pre-capitalizations</h2>
</td>
</tr>
</table>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Meanwhile in more normal M&amp;A, a common for=
m of acquisition is the leveraged buyout (LBO) by a private equity firm: So=
me company puts itself up for auction, a few private equity firms bid, and =
one of them wins and buys the company. The buyer generally borrows a lot of=
 the money needed to buy the company, with that borrowing coming either fro=
m bonds and loans underwritten by one or more big banks, or (more recently)=
 from private credit lenders. Traditionally that lending business is a huge=
 (<a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/34412285.257387/=
aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYnVzaW5lc3NpbnNpZGVyLmNvbS9lbG9uLW11c2stdHdpdHRlci1idXlvdXQ=
tZGVhbC14LWJhbmtzLWxvYW5zLWxvc3Nlcy1sZW5kZXJzLTIwMjMtMTI/607f07ceef4b8524a3=
19a23cB1cf43e11" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_=
blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bo=
ttom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; =
background-color: #ccc;">though risky</a>) source of revenue for the banks,=
 who can make more on the fees from the financing than they do on mergers-a=
nd-acquisitions advisory fees.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">And so a certain amount of M&amp;A structuring=
 is built around banks=E2=80=99 desire to get financing fees. For instance,=
 traditionally, the company selling itself will hire a bank as an=C2=A0advi=
ser, and the potential buyers will each hire their own bank, who will advis=
e them on the deal and also provide their=C2=A0financing (if they win the a=
uction). But this means that the company=E2=80=99s bankers won=E2=80=99t ge=
t any financing fees, which is a bummer for them. So some deals come with =
=E2=80=9Cstapled financing,=E2=80=9D in which the seller=E2=80=99s bankers =
offer to provide financing for=C2=A0the winning bidder: This perhaps <a hre=
f=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/34412285.257387/aHR0cHM6=
Ly93d3cuYmF1ZXIudWguZWR1L3BvdmVsL2RvY3VtZW50cy9zdGFwbGVkZmluLnBkZg/607f07ce=
ef4b8524a319a23cB7702e817" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" t=
arget=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important;=
 border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-styl=
e: solid; background-color: #ccc;"> makes the auction more competitive</a>,=
 but it also means that the seller=E2=80=99s bankers have a chance to get f=
inancing fees.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">I guess another option would be to do the fina=
ncing first=C2=A0and=C2=A0<em>then=C2=A0</em>sell the company? Like, if you=
 are a company that might want to sell itself (or the company=E2=80=99s ban=
ker), you can probably build an LBO model yourself and estimate roughly wha=
t sort of capital structure =E2=80=94=C2=A0how much borrowing, what kind an=
d at what rates =E2=80=94=C2=A0a private equity borrower might want. And th=
en you go do the borrowing yourself. And then you run the auction, and say =
to potential buyers =E2=80=9Chey this capital structure is already set up s=
o nice for you, all we need is your equity check.=E2=80=9D=C2=A0</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Why not. Bloomberg=E2=80=99s=C2=A0<a href=3D"h=
ttps://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/34412285.257387/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3=
cuYmxvb21iZXJnLmNvbS9uZXdzL2FydGljbGVzLzIwMjQtMDItMTkvd2FsbC1zdHJlZXQtYmFua=
3MtYXJlLXRyeWluZy1ldmVyeXRoaW5nLWluLWZpZ2h0LXRvLXdpbi11bmRlcndyaXRpbmctZGVh=
bHM_Y21waWQ9QkJEMDIyMDI0X01PTkVZU1RVRkYmdXRtX21lZGl1bT1lbWFpbCZ1dG1fc291cmN=
lPW5ld3NsZXR0ZXImdXRtX3Rlcm09MjQwMjIwJnV0bV9jYW1wYWlnbj1tb25leXN0dWZm/607f0=
7ceef4b8524a319a23cBe5508e32" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope=
" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !importa=
nt; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-s=
tyle: solid; background-color: #ccc;">Eleanor Duncan and Michael Tobin repo=
rt</a>=C2=A0that big banks are trying to win business back from private cre=
dit, both by sort of lowering their standards and by offering =E2=80=9Cpre-=
capitaliations=E2=80=9D:</p>
<blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Traditional lenders are so keen to win leverag=
ed buyout financing that some are pitching for subordinated debt deals =E2=
=80=94 the riskiest type of underwriting which they mostly avoided during a=
 bruising past few years. At least one bank is offering payment-in-kind opt=
ions, which allow interest payments to be deferred, and others are talking =
to borrowers about so-called pre-capitalizations, which give companies fina=
ncing before a deal has even gone on the block, according to people familia=
r with the matter. =E2=80=A6</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The quest to win fees is driving some banks, i=
ncluding Bank of America, to pitch pre-capitalizations to companies that ar=
en=E2=80=99t even for sale yet, according to a person familiar with the mat=
ter. In these deals, lenders refinance a firm=E2=80=99s debt and add a port=
ability clause, allowing a new buyer to keep the existing debt package in p=
lace. Bankers say it makes it easier for companies to be sold at a later da=
te because the new owner doesn=E2=80=99t have to find financing.</p>
</blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Presumably this makes the most sense for compa=
nies with private equity owners (who might shop them to=C2=A0<em>new </em>p=
rivate equity owners), which already have LBO-ish capital structures that t=
hey just want to be portable.</p>
