olor: #ccc;">  times</a> about the US Securities and Exchange Commission=E2=
=80=99s insider trading case against Matthew Panuwat, who is accused of sha=
dow trading on merger news. (He allegedly knew his employer was getting acq=
uired, so he bought options on a competitor, whose stock also went up on th=
e acquisition news.) Today the Wall Street Journal <a href=3D"https://link.=
mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/34412285.257387/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cud3NqLmNvbS=
9maW5hbmNlL3JlZ3VsYXRpb24vYW4tZXhlY3V0aXZlLWJvdWdodC1hLXJpdmFscy1zdG9jay10a=
GUtc2VjLXNheXMtdGhhdHMtaW5zaWRlci10cmFkaW5nLTg0ZWY4YWFlP21vZD1ocF9sZWFkX3Bv=
czM/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB6b469109" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"=
itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none=
 !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border=
-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;"> covers the case</a>:</p>
<blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The case, which goes to trial next month, has =
become the latest test of insider-trading law. Congress has never defined w=
hat it means, leaving regulators and courts across the country to decide wh=
at qualifies, a volatile process that sometimes leads appellate courts to r=
ein in what they see as excesses.=C2=A0</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Defense lawyers have dubbed Panuwat=E2=80=99s =
case the first involving =E2=80=9Cshadow insider trading,=E2=80=9D a label =
that describes executives making well-timed bets in the shares of other com=
panies. =E2=80=A6</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">No court has ever tackled the idea that execut=
ives can go too far when they deploy their specialized knowledge or experti=
se to trade in the shares of rivals, said Karen Woody, a professor at the W=
ashington and Lee University School of Law.=C2=A0</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">=E2=80=9CI do think this is a push of the law =
and they are seeing if they can get a court to bless what is a bit of a str=
etch of the existing parameters,=E2=80=9D Woody said of the SEC=E2=80=99s c=
ase.</p>
</blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">I mean, on the one hand, that=E2=80=99s true, =
but on the other hand, imagine if the court said =E2=80=9Cnah that just isn=
=E2=80=99t insider trading=E2=80=9D? (I don=E2=80=99t think that=E2=80=99s =
likely, since the judge has declined to dismiss the case. The SEC might sti=
ll lose at trial, but if it does, that will probably be an inscrutable jury=
 verdict that doesn't really define the law for future cases. But if the SE=
C <em>wins</em> at trial, Panuwat could appeal, and then an appeals court c=
ould still say =E2=80=9Cnah, not insider trading.=E2=80=9D) Then every=C2=
=A0<em>sophisticated=C2=A0</em>corporate insider =E2=80=94=C2=A0also, sorry=
, every Money Stuff reader =E2=80=94=C2=A0would have a blueprint for how to=
 do insider trading legally. You find out your company=E2=80=99s news and y=
ou go trade the most correlated stock.=C2=A0</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">I have said this before, but for years readers=
 have emailed me with some variation on this idea. =E2=80=9CIf I have insid=
e information about my company, can I trade our competitor=E2=80=99s stock,=
 knowing that the news is probably good for them too?=E2=80=9D My general t=
houghts on this question used to be (1) nothing here is ever legal advice, =
(2) the SEC=C2=A0wouldn=E2=80=99t like it and (3) the law is arguably a lit=
tle unclear, since there are no real precedents. That state of affairs prob=
ably deterred at least some people from doing shadow trading: Why do someth=
ing the SEC thinks is illegal, even if the law is unclear?</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">But now the SEC has brought a case, which has =
the advantage and disadvantage that it might resolve the ambiguity. On the =
one hand, now you=C2=A0<em>definitely=C2=A0</em>know that the SEC doesn=E2=
=80=99t like shadow trading, which might be an additional deterrent. On the=
 other hand, what if the SEC loses? What if the answer is =E2=80=9Cnot lega=
l advice, the SEC won=E2=80=99t like it, but courts say=C2=A0it=E2=80=99s a=
llowed so there=E2=80=99s nothing the SEC can do about it=E2=80=9D? I suspe=
ct that will mean much more shadow trading.=C2=A0</p>
